0-04-02}}</ref>\n\n* Trokosi\n* Total Exchange\n* Cross My Heart\n* My Darling Princess\n* June 4th\n* Araba Lawson\n* Big Girl Club\n* Girls Connection\n* True Colour\n* Pretty Queen\n* Tears of Womanhood\n* The Return of Beyonce\n* The  Bible\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Ghanaian actresses]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian film actresses]]\n\n{{Ghana-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jwale2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vicky_Zugah"}
{"title_page": "Black Salt Collective", "text_new": "'''Black Salt Collective''' is an American [[queer]], women-of-color artist collective<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.soex.org/black-salt-collective|title=Black Salt Collective|date=2014-04-11|work=Southern Exposure|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en}}</ref> that currently consists of four [[California]]-based artists and curators: [[Sarah Biscarra-Dilley]], [[Grace Rosario Perkins]], Anna Luisa Petrisko, and Adee Roberson.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/art/article/Artists-carving-out-space-for-women-of-color-in-6762743.php|title=Artists carving out space for women of color in art world|last=Kost|first=Ryan|date=2016-01-15|work=SFGate|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> Founded in 2012, Black Salt Collective's art practice crosses disciplines and media, including performance, [[video]], installation, [[Sound recording and reproduction|sound]], [[painting]], [[collage]], [[Textile|textiles]], [[sculpture]], and [[printmaking]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== History ==\nFounding member Anna Luisa Petrisko has explained that, among other commonalities, the group's members \"all make artwork with the intention of healing. Healing ourselves, healing our communities, healing the past and healing the future.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thelesigh.com/2013/07/collective-black-salt.html|title=Collective: Black Salt|website=www.thelesigh.com|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> The group is known for expanding narratives of art practice and [[art history]] beyond male, Eurocentric points of view.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/29169/1/the-art-collective-reimagining-the-past-and-future-for-woc|title=The art collective reimagining the past and future for WOC|last=Dazed|date=2016-01-14|work=Dazed|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs an artist collective, Black Salt Collective has exhibited at [[Artists' Television Access|Artists\u2019 Television Access]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atasite.org/2013/03/black-salt-collective/|title=Black Salt Collective \u2013 Artists' Television Access|website=www.atasite.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.browntourage.com/magazine/black-salt-collective-ft-jeepneys-at-ata-gallery/|title=BLACK SALT COLLECTIVE FT. JEEPNEYS at ATA Gallery|date=2013-03-09|work=BROWNTOURAGE MOVED TO BROWNTOURAGE.COM|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en-US}}</ref> the [[San Francisco Public Library]] (as part of the Radar Reading Series),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sfpl.org/?pg=1014109001|title=*Radar Reading Series|website=SFPL|language=en|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> MIX Festival, [[The Outsider Festival|Outsider Festival]], and Glitch Festival Australia.<ref name=\"openengagement.info\">{{Cite web|url=http://openengagement.info/speaker/black-salt-collective/|title=Black Salt Collective {{!}} Open Engagement|website=openengagement.info|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> Black Salt Collective was a recipient of a [[Southern Exposure (art space)|Southern Exposure]] grant in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://soex.org/black-salt-collective|title=Round 7|last=|first=|date=April 2, 2020|website=Southern Exposure|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  In 2016 Black Salt Collective participated in the Artist in Residence Program at Facebook.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13689222/women-to-watch-black-salt-collective|title=Women to Watch: Black Salt Collective|last=Hotchkiss|first=Sarah|date=Jul 20, 2017|website=KQED|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As a curatorial collective, Black Salt Collective has held a curatorial residency at SOMArts (2016) resulting in the [[exhibition]] \"Visions into Infinite Archives.\"<ref name=\"somarts.org\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.somarts.org/infinitearchives/|title=Black Salt Collective\u2019s Visions Into Infinite Archives \u2014 SOMArts|website=www.somarts.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328022257/http://www.somarts.org/infinitearchives/|archive-date=2017-03-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> They have spoken at the Open Engagement conference (2016),<ref name=\"openengagement.info\"/> the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ccs.ucsb.edu/news-and-events/events/spring-2016-arts-colloquium-black-salt-collective|title=Spring 2016 Arts Colloquium: Black Salt Collective  {{!}} UCSB College of Creative Studies|website=www.ccs.ucsb.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328021008/https://www.ccs.ucsb.edu/news-and-events/events/spring-2016-arts-colloquium-black-salt-collective|archive-date=2017-03-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Occidental College]] (2017).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oxy.edu/events/oxy-arts-speaker-series-black-salt-collective|title=Oxy Arts Speaker Series: Black Salt Collective {{!}} Occidental College {{!}} The Liberal Arts College in Los Angeles|website=www.oxy.edu|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n== Projects and exhibitions ==\n\n===''Visions Into Infinite Archives''===\nBlack Salt Collective's curatorial residency opened in January 2016 in SOMArt\u2019s Main Gallery with the exhibition \u201cVisions into Infinite Archives.\u201d featured 30 artists and [[Filmmaking|filmmakers]] of color.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ww2.kqed.org/arts/2016/01/14/black-salt-collective-agitates-the-archive-with-visions-at-somarts/|title=Black Salt Collective Agitates the Archive with \u2018Visions\u2019 at SOMArts|work=KQED Arts|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en-us}}</ref><ref name=\"somarts.org\"/> The exhibition has been described as \"energetically showcas[ing] a wide spectrum of artists of color engaging in equally varied disciplinary and conceptual approaches\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://temporaryartreview.com/visions-into-infinite-archives-at-somarts/|title=Visions Into Infinite Archives at SOMArts {{!}} Temporary Art Review|website=temporaryartreview.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> while also \" putting elements of their ancestry in dialogue with their lived experiences through inventive [[Juxtaposition|juxtapositions]], many offering visions of [[Utopia|utopian]] futures.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eastbayexpress.com/oakland/visions-into-infinite-archives-resists-the-neat-tidy-and-eurocentric/Content?oid=4655539|title='Visions into Infinite Archives' Resists the Neat, Tidy, and Eurocentric|last=Voynovskaya|first=Nastia|website=East Bay Express|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n===''Space and Place''===\nA [[multimedia]] exhibition featuring images and video of the Black Salt Collective members singing and dancing in the confines of a room.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sactownmag.com/The-Weekender/2018/Sacramento-Museum-Day/|title=Explore these 10 museums and cultural centers for free on Sacramento Museum Day|last=Chao|first=Vu|date=2018-01-31|work=SacTown magazine|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> This was shown at the [[Verge Center for the Arts]] in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] in 2018.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Artists from California]]\n[[Category:American artist groups and collectives]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:LGBT artists from the United States]]\n[[Category:African-American arts organizations]]\n", "text_old": "'''Black Salt Collective''' is an American [[queer]], women-of-color artist collective<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.soex.org/black-salt-collective|title=Black Salt Collective|date=2014-04-11|work=Southern Exposure|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en}}</ref> that currently consists of four [[California]]-based artists and curators: [[Sarah Biscarra-Dilley]], [[Grace Rosario Perkins]], Anna Luisa Petrisko, and Adee Roberson.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/art/article/Artists-carving-out-space-for-women-of-color-in-6762743.php|title=Artists carving out space for women of color in art world|last=Kost|first=Ryan|date=2016-01-15|work=SFGate|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> Founded in 2012, Black Salt Collective's art practice crosses disciplines and media, including performance, [[video]], installation, [[Sound recording and reproduction|sound]], [[painting]], [[collage]], [[Textile|textiles]], [[sculpture]], and [[printmaking]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== History ==\nFounding member Anna Luisa Petrisko has explained that, among other commonalities, the group's members \"all make artwork with the intention of healing. Healing ourselves, healing our communities, healing the past and healing the future.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thelesigh.com/2013/07/collective-black-salt.html|title=Collective: Black Salt|website=www.thelesigh.com|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> The group is known for expanding narratives of art practice and [[art history]] beyond male, Eurocentric points of view.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/29169/1/the-art-collective-reimagining-the-past-and-future-for-woc|title=The art collective reimagining the past and future for WOC|last=Dazed|date=2016-01-14|work=Dazed|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs an artist collective, Black Salt Collective has exhibited at [[Artists' Television Access|Artists\u2019 Television Access]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atasite.org/2013/03/black-salt-collective/|title=Black Salt Collective \u2013 Artists' Television Access|website=www.atasite.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.browntourage.com/magazine/black-salt-collective-ft-jeepneys-at-ata-gallery/|title=BLACK SALT COLLECTIVE FT. JEEPNEYS at ATA Gallery|date=2013-03-09|work=BROWNTOURAGE MOVED TO BROWNTOURAGE.COM|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en-US}}</ref> the [[San Francisco Public Library]] (as part of the Radar Reading Series),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sfpl.org/?pg=1014109001|title=*Radar Reading Series|website=SFPL|language=en|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> MIX Festival, [[The Outsider Festival|Outsider Festival]], and Glitch Festival Australia.<ref name=\"openengagement.info\">{{Cite web|url=http://openengagement.info/speaker/black-salt-collective/|title=Black Salt Collective {{!}} Open Engagement|website=openengagement.info|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> In 2016 Black Salt Collective participated in the Artist in Residence Program at Facebook.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13689222/women-to-watch-black-salt-collective|title=Women to Watch: Black Salt Collective|last=Hotchkiss|first=Sarah|date=Jul 20, 2017|website=KQED|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As a curatorial collective, Black Salt Collective has held a curatorial residency at SOMArts (2016) resulting in the [[exhibition]] \"Visions into Infinite Archives.\"<ref name=\"somarts.org\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.somarts.org/infinitearchives/|title=Black Salt Collective\u2019s Visions Into Infinite Archives \u2014 SOMArts|website=www.somarts.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328022257/http://www.somarts.org/infinitearchives/|archive-date=2017-03-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> They have spoken at the Open Engagement conference (2016),<ref name=\"openengagement.info\"/> the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ccs.ucsb.edu/news-and-events/events/spring-2016-arts-colloquium-black-salt-collective|title=Spring 2016 Arts Colloquium: Black Salt Collective  {{!}} UCSB College of Creative Studies|website=www.ccs.ucsb.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328021008/https://www.ccs.ucsb.edu/news-and-events/events/spring-2016-arts-colloquium-black-salt-collective|archive-date=2017-03-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Occidental College]] (2017).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oxy.edu/events/oxy-arts-speaker-series-black-salt-collective|title=Oxy Arts Speaker Series: Black Salt Collective {{!}} Occidental College {{!}} The Liberal Arts College in Los Angeles|website=www.oxy.edu|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n== Projects and exhibitions ==\n\n===''Visions Into Infinite Archives''===\nBlack Salt Collective's curatorial residency opened in January 2016 in SOMArt\u2019s Main Gallery with the exhibition \u201cVisions into Infinite Archives.\u201d featured 30 artists and [[Filmmaking|filmmakers]] of color.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ww2.kqed.org/arts/2016/01/14/black-salt-collective-agitates-the-archive-with-visions-at-somarts/|title=Black Salt Collective Agitates the Archive with \u2018Visions\u2019 at SOMArts|work=KQED Arts|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en-us}}</ref><ref name=\"somarts.org\"/> The exhibition has been described as \"energetically showcas[ing] a wide spectrum of artists of color engaging in equally varied disciplinary and conceptual approaches\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://temporaryartreview.com/visions-into-infinite-archives-at-somarts/|title=Visions Into Infinite Archives at SOMArts {{!}} Temporary Art Review|website=temporaryartreview.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> while also \" putting elements of their ancestry in dialogue with their lived experiences through inventive [[Juxtaposition|juxtapositions]], many offering visions of [[Utopia|utopian]] futures.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eastbayexpress.com/oakland/visions-into-infinite-archives-resists-the-neat-tidy-and-eurocentric/Content?oid=4655539|title='Visions into Infinite Archives' Resists the Neat, Tidy, and Eurocentric|last=Voynovskaya|first=Nastia|website=East Bay Express|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n===''Space and Place''===\nA [[multimedia]] exhibition featuring images and video of the Black Salt Collective members singing and dancing in the confines of a room.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sactownmag.com/The-Weekender/2018/Sacramento-Museum-Day/|title=Explore these 10 museums and cultural centers for free on Sacramento Museum Day|last=Chao|first=Vu|date=2018-01-31|work=SacTown magazine|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> This was shown at the [[Verge Center for the Arts]] in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] in 2018.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Artists from California]]\n[[Category:American artist groups and collectives]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:LGBT artists from the United States]]\n[[Category:African-American arts organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Hammyburgy", "label": "safe", "comment": "added SOEX grant info", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Salt_Collective"}
{"title_page": "Inter-Allied Games", "text_new": "{{nofootnotes|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox games\n| name                   = Inter-Allied Games\n| logo                   = Inter-AlliedGames.jpg\n| size                   = 200px\n| caption                = The poster for the Inter-Allied Games, depicting an athlete jumping over the flags of the Allied Nations.\n| host city              = [[Paris]]\n| country                = France\n| motto                  = \n| nations participating  =\n| teams participating    = \n| debuting countries     =\n| athletes participating = \n| events                 = \n| opening ceremony       = {{Start date|1919|6|22|df=y}}\n| closing ceremony       = {{End date|1919|7|6|df=y}}\n| officially opened by   = \n| athlete's oath         = \n| judge's oath           = \n| torch lighter          = \n| stadium                = \n| length                 = \n| indprize               = \n| tmprize                = \n| website                = \n| previous               = \n| next                   = \n}}\n[[File:L'\u00e9quipe am\u00e9ricaine \u00e0 la c\u00e9r\u00e9monie d'ouverture des Jeux Interalli\u00e9s de 1919.jpg|thumb|alt=parade|The American team at the opening ceremony of the 1919 Inter-Allied Games]]\n[[File:US Army Band marching in opening ceremonies of the Inter Allied Games - Pershing stadium Paris France 22 June 1919.jpg|thumb|alt=parade|American Army Band marching in the opening ceremonies of the Inter-Allied Games - Pershing stadium, Paris, France, 22 June 1919]]\nThe '''Inter-Allied Games''' was a one-off multi-sport event held from 22 June to 6 July 1919 at the newly constructed [[Stade Pershing|Pershing Stadium]] just outside [[Paris]], [[France]] following the end of [[World War I]]. The host stadium had been built near the [[Bois de Vincennes]] by the U.S. Military in cooperation with the [[YMCA]]. The event was only open to participation by military personnel who were currently serving or had formerly served in the armed forces during the War. Around 1500 athletes from a total of eighteen nations participated in the proceedings which featured nineteen sports. Following the conclusion of the games, Pershing Stadium was presented as a gift to the people of France from the United States of America.  The area, still known as Le Stade Pershing, continues to be used as an open air recreation park to this day.\n\n==Sports==\nA total of nineteen sports were contested at the games. A number of military-oriented events was initially planned, but only [[hand-grenade]] throwing and shooting made it on to the final programme.\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n*{{GamesSport|American football}}\n*{{GamesSport|Association football}}\n*{{GamesSport|Athletics}}\n*{{GamesSport|Baseball}}\n*{{GamesSport|Basketball}}\n*{{GamesSport|Boxing}}\n*{{GamesSport|Cross country running}}\n*{{GamesSport|Equestrian}}\n*{{GamesSport|Fencing}}\n*{{GamesSport|Golf}}\n*{{GamesSport|Hand-grenade throwing}}\n*{{GamesSport|Rowing}}\n*{{GamesSport|Rugby union}}\n*{{GamesSport|Shooting}}\n*{{GamesSport|Swimming}}\n*{{GamesSport|Tennis}}\n*{{GamesSport|Tug of war}}\n*{{GamesSport|Water polo}}\n*{{GamesSport|Wrestling}}\n}}\n\n==Participating nations==\nA total of twenty-eight nations from the [[Allies of World War I]] were invited to the competition and eighteen nations accepted the invite. China aimed to compete, but ultimately was unable to send any athletes to the games within the timescale. It did, however, provide medals and trophies in support of the games. The [[Kingdom of Hejaz]] sent a delegation but with no athletes, choosing to demonstrate the skills of their Arabian horsemen instead. A full list of participants was made by the organisers.\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n*{{AUS}}\n*{{BEL}}\n*{{flagcountry|BRA|1889}}\n*{{flagcountry|CAN|1868}}\n*{{flagcountry|TCH}}\n*{{FRA}}\n*{{GBR2}}\n*{{flagcountry|GRE|old}}\n*{{GUA}} (1)\n*[[File:Flag of Hejaz 1920.svg|25px]] [[Kingdom of Hejaz]]\n*{{flagcountry|ITA|1861}}\n*{{flagcountry|Newfoundland}} (1)\n*{{NZL}}\n*{{POL}} (1)\n*{{POR}}\n*{{ROM}}\n*{{flagcountry|Kingdom of Serbia}}\n*{{flagcountry|USA|1912}}\n}}\n\n==Gold medalists==\nThese athletes competed in and won gold medals at the 1919 Inter-Allied Games:\n*[[Ralph Parcaut]] - Gold Medal, Light Heavyweight Division, Catch as Catch Can Wrestling\n*[[Paul Prehn]] - Gold Medal, Middleweight Division, Catch as Catch Can Wrestling\n*[[Gene Tunney]] - Gold Medal, Boxing\n*[[Max Friedman]] - Gold medal, Basketball\n*[[Norman Ross]] - 5 Gold Medals, Swimming\n*Carl F. Haas, William Clinton Gray, Floyd F. Campbell, and Lawrence M. Shields - Medley Relay Race\n*United States of America, First Place, Rifle Shooting Team, Team Members include - Brigadier General Paul A. Wolf\n\n==References==\n*Bell, Daniel (2003). ''Encyclopedia of International Games''. McFarland and Company, Inc. Publishers, Jefferson, North Carolina. {{ISBN|0-7864-1026-4}}.\n*[https://archive.org/stream/cu31924014114353/cu31924014114353_djvu.txt Full text of ''The inter-allied games, Paris, 22nd June to 6th July, 1919'']. Albert R Mann, Cornell University Library.\n\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Inter-allied games}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151102021328/http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1919.html Report on football tournament]\n*[http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/ialg.htm List Track and Field results]\n*[http://hoopedia.nba.com/index.php?title=Inter-Allied_Games A description of the basketball tournament]\n\n{{multi-sport events}}\n\n[[Category:Multi-sport events in France]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Paris]]\n[[Category:1919 in multi-sport events]]\n[[Category:1919 in French sport]]\n[[Category:World War I]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions hosted by France]]\n[[Category:Defunct multi-sport events]]\n[[Category:1919 in European sport]]\n[[Category:June 1919 events]]\n[[Category:July 1919 events]]\n[[Category:1919 in Paris]]\n", "text_old": "{{nofootnotes|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox games\n| name                   = Inter-Allied Games\n| logo                   = Inter-AlliedGames.jpg\n| size                   = 200px\n| caption                = The poster for the Inter-Allied Games, depicting an athlete jumping over the flags of the Allied Nations.\n| host city              = [[Paris]]\n| country                = France\n| motto                  = \n| nations participating  =\n| teams participating    = \n| debuting countries     =\n| athletes participating = \n| events                 = \n| opening ceremony       = {{Start date|1919|6|22|df=y}}\n| closing ceremony       = {{End date|1919|7|6|df=y}}\n| officially opened by   = \n| athlete's oath         = \n| judge's oath           = \n| torch lighter          = \n| stadium                = \n| length                 = \n| indprize               = \n| tmprize                = \n| website                = \n| previous               = \n| next                   = \n}}\n[[File:L'\u00e9quipe am\u00e9ricaine \u00e0 la c\u00e9r\u00e9monie d'ouverture des Jeux Interalli\u00e9s de 1919.jpg|thumb|alt=parade|The American team at the opening ceremony of the 1919 Inter-Allied Games]]\n[[File:US Army Band marching in opening ceremonies of the Inter Allied Games - Pershing stadium Paris France 22 June 1919.jpg|thumb|alt=parade|American Army Band marching in the opening ceremonies of the Inter-Allied Games - Pershing stadium, Paris, France, 22 June 1919]]\nThe '''Inter-Allied Games''' was a one-off multi-sport event held from 22 June to 6 July 1919 at the newly constructed [[Stade Pershing|Pershing Stadium]] just outside [[Paris]], [[France]] following the end of [[World War I]]. The host stadium had been built near the [[Bois de Vincennes]] by the U.S. Military in cooperation with the [[YMCA]]. The event was only open to participation by military personnel who were currently serving or had formerly served in the armed forces during the War. Around 1500 athletes from a total of eighteen nations participated in the proceedings which featured nineteen sports. Following the conclusion of the games, Pershing Stadium was presented as a gift to the people of France from the United States of America.  The area, still known as Le Stade Pershing, continues to be used as an open air recreation park to this day.\n\n==Sports==\nA total of nineteen sports were contested at the games. A number of military-oriented events was initially planned, but only [[hand-grenade]] throwing and shooting made it on to the final programme.\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n*{{GamesSport|American football}}\n*{{GamesSport|Association football}}\n*{{GamesSport|Athletics}}\n*{{GamesSport|Baseball}}\n*{{GamesSport|Basketball}}\n*{{GamesSport|Boxing}}\n*{{GamesSport|Cross country running}}\n*{{GamesSport|Equestrian}}\n*{{GamesSport|Fencing}}\n*{{GamesSport|Golf}}\n*{{GamesSport|Hand-grenade throwing}}\n*{{GamesSport|Rowing}}\n*{{GamesSport|Rugby union}}\n*{{GamesSport|Shooting}}\n*{{GamesSport|Swimming}}\n*{{GamesSport|Tennis}}\n*{{GamesSport|Tug of war}}\n*{{GamesSport|Water polo}}\n*{{GamesSport|Wrestling}}\n}}\n\n==Participating nations==\nA total of twenty-eight nations from the [[Allies of World War I]] were invited to the competition and eighteen nations accepted the invite. China aimed to compete, but ultimately was unable to send any athletes to the games within the time scale. It did, however, provide medals and trophies in support of the games. The [[Kingdom of Hejaz]] sent a delegation but with no athletes, choosing to demonstrate the skills of their Arabian horsemen instead. A full list of participants was made by the organisers.\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n*{{AUS}}\n*{{BEL}}\n*{{flagcountry|BRA|1889}}\n*{{flagcountry|CAN|1868}}\n*{{flagcountry|TCH}}\n*{{FRA}}\n*{{GBR2}}\n*{{flagcountry|GRE|old}}\n*{{GUA}} (1)\n*[[File:Flag of Hejaz 1920.svg|25px]] [[Kingdom of Hejaz]]\n*{{flagcountry|ITA|1861}}\n*{{flagcountry|Newfoundland}} (1)\n*{{NZL}}\n*{{POL}} (1)\n*{{POR}}\n*{{ROM}}\n*{{flagcountry|Kingdom of Serbia}}\n*{{flagcountry|USA|1912}}\n}}\n\n==Gold medalists==\nThese athletes competed in and won gold medals at the 1919 Inter-Allied Games:\n*[[Ralph Parcaut]] - Gold Medal, Light Heavyweight Division, Catch as Catch Can Wrestling\n*[[Paul Prehn]] - Gold Medal, Middleweight Division, Catch as Catch Can Wrestling\n*[[Gene Tunney]] - Gold Medal, Boxing\n*[[Max Friedman]] - Gold medal, Basketball\n*[[Norman Ross]] - 5 Gold Medals, Swimming\n*Carl F. Haas, William Clinton Gray, Floyd F. Campbell, and Lawrence M. Shields - Medley Relay Race\n*United States of America, First Place, Rifle Shooting Team, Team Members include - Brigadier General Paul A. Wolf\n\n==References==\n*Bell, Daniel (2003). ''Encyclopedia of International Games''. McFarland and Company, Inc. Publishers, Jefferson, North Carolina. {{ISBN|0-7864-1026-4}}.\n*[https://archive.org/stream/cu31924014114353/cu31924014114353_djvu.txt Full text of ''The inter-allied games, Paris, 22nd June to 6th July, 1919'']. Albert R Mann, Cornell University Library.\n\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Inter-allied games}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151102021328/http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1919.html Report on football tournament]\n*[http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/ialg.htm List Track and Field results]\n*[http://hoopedia.nba.com/index.php?title=Inter-Allied_Games A description of the basketball tournament]\n\n{{multi-sport events}}\n\n[[Category:Multi-sport events in France]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Paris]]\n[[Category:1919 in multi-sport events]]\n[[Category:1919 in French sport]]\n[[Category:World War I]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions hosted by France]]\n[[Category:Defunct multi-sport events]]\n[[Category:1919 in European sport]]\n[[Category:June 1919 events]]\n[[Category:July 1919 events]]\n[[Category:1919 in Paris]]\n", "name_user": "Onanoff", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eParticipating nations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inter-Allied_Games"}
{"title_page": "Marmoset (music agency)", "text_new": "{{advert|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Marmoset\n| founded = 2010\n| industry = {{hlist | [[Music]] | [[advertising]] | [[film]] | [[broadcast]]}}\n| location = [[Portland, Oregon]], US\n| founders = {{hlist | Ryan Wines | Brian Hall}}\n| num_employees = 45\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| services = {{hlist | [[Music licensing]] | original music production | music clearances | [[sound design]] | [[music composition]] | [[music education]] | [[sync license|sync licensing]]}}\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.marmosetmusic.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Marmoset''' is a music agency with headquarters in Portland, Oregon. Founded in 2010 by Ryan Wines and Brian Hall, Marmoset represents vintage and independent artists, bands, and record labels for licensing.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/blog/2014/02/40-under-40-marmosets-ryan-wines.html|title=Marmosets Ryan Wines |date=2014 |website=www.bizjournals.com}}</ref> Marmoset's Music Production Team specializes in creating original music, soundtracks, and scores for brand campaigns, film, and television. \nMarmoset\u2019s clients include [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], [[Google]], [[Levi\u2019s]], [[Facebook]], [[Coca-Cola]], [[Wieden + Kennedy]], [[Droga5]], [[Ogilvy & Mather|Ogilvy]], [[BBDO]], [[DDB Worldwide|DDB]], [[Crispin Porter + Bogusky|CP+B]], [[Goodby, Silverstein & Partners|Goodby Silverstein]], [[Grey Global Group|Grey Worldwide]], [[McCann (company)|McCann]], [[Leo Burnett]].  \nThe music agency has also developed a music search and licensing platform at marmosetmusic.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webbyawards.com/winners/2014/web/general-website/shopping/marmoset-music/|title=Marmoset Music - The Webby Awards|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Capabilities==\nMarmoset\u2019s main services are Music Production Team and Music Licensing. The search tool offers advanced music filtering technology, allowing users to find and license music easily with custom search elements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inc.com/noah-davis/2015-inc5000-how-this-entrepreneur-helped-put-portlands-music-scene-on-the-map.html|title=How This Entrepreneur Helped Put Portland's Music Scene on the Map|date=23 November 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2010 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Portland, Oregon]]\n\n\n{{music-company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Marmoset\n| founded = 2010\n| industry = {{hlist | [[Music]] | [[advertising]] | [[film]] | [[broadcast]]}}\n| location = [[Portland, Oregon]], US\n| founders = {{hlist | Ryan Wines | Brian Hall}}\n| num_employees = 45\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| services = {{hlist | [[Music licensing]] | original music production | music clearances | [[sound design]] | [[music composition]] | [[music education]] | [[sync license|sync licensing]]}}\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.marmosetmusic.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Marmoset''' is a music agency with headquarters in Portland, Oregon. Founded in 2010 by Ryan Wines and Brian Hall, Marmoset is represents vintage and independent artists, bands, and record labels, for licensing.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/blog/2014/02/40-under-40-marmosets-ryan-wines.html|title=Marmosets Ryan Wines |date=2014 |website=www.bizjournals.com}}</ref> Marmoset's Music Production Team specializes in creating original music, soundtracks, and scores for brand campaigns, film, and television. \nMarmoset\u2019s clients include [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], [[Google]], [[Levi\u2019s]], [[Facebook]], [[Coca-Cola]], [[Wieden + Kennedy]], [[Droga5]], [[Ogilvy & Mather|Ogilvy]], [[BBDO]], [[DDB Worldwide|DDB]], [[Crispin Porter + Bogusky|CP+B]], [[Goodby, Silverstein & Partners|Goodby Silverstein]], [[Grey Global Group|Grey Worldwide]], [[McCann (company)|McCann]], [[Leo Burnett]].  \nThe music agency has also developed a music search and licensing platform at marmosetmusic.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webbyawards.com/winners/2014/web/general-website/shopping/marmoset-music/|title=Marmoset Music - The Webby Awards|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Capabilities==\nMarmoset\u2019s main services are Music Production Team and Music Licensing. The search tool offers advanced music filtering technology, allowing users to find and license music easily with custom search elements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inc.com/noah-davis/2015-inc5000-how-this-entrepreneur-helped-put-portlands-music-scene-on-the-map.html|title=How This Entrepreneur Helped Put Portland's Music Scene on the Map|date=23 November 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2010 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Portland, Oregon]]\n\n\n{{music-company-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Montezuma Jones", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marmoset_(music_agency)"}
