0e8re des Prairies]]'', [[Laval, Quebec|Laval]]\n|Northeast=''[[Rivi\u00e8re des Prairies]]'', [[Repentigny, Quebec|Repentigny]]\n|Southwest=''[[Saint Lawrence River]]'', [[La Prairie, Quebec|La Prairie]], [[Candiac, Quebec|Candiac]]\n|Southeast=''[[Saint Lawrence River]]'', [[Longueuil]]\n}}\n{{Montreal}}\n{{Navboxes|list =\n{{Montreal landmarks}}\n{{Streets in Montreal}}\n{{MontrealNeighbourhoods}}\n{{Greater Montreal}}\n{{Subdivisions of Quebec|cities=yes|region=Montreal}}\n{{Olympic Summer Games Host Cities}}\n{{World Book Capital}}\n{{Montreal tallest buildings}}}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Quebec]]\n[[Category:Montreal| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:1832 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Administrative regions of Quebec]]\n[[Category:Former colonial capitals in Canada]]\n[[Category:French mission settlements in North America]]\n[[Category:Hudson's Bay Company trading posts]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1642]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Saint Lawrence River]]\n[[Category:Port settlements in Quebec]]\n", "name_user": "Andrybak", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:fix navbox collapsing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montreal"}
{"title_page": "Patrick Lyon, 1st Earl of Kinghorne", "text_new": "'''Patrick Lyon, 1st Earl of Kinghorne''' (c. 1575\u20131615) was a Scottish landowner.\n\nPatrick Lyon was the son of [[John Lyon, 8th Lord Glamis]] and Elizabeth Abernethy, only daughter of [[Alexander Abernethy, 6th Lord Saltoun]].\n[[File:Entrance to Glamis Castle - geograph.org.uk - 918221.jpg|thumb|right|The spiral stair at [[Glamis Castle]] was the work of Patrick Lyon, Earl of Kinghorne]]\nHis father was killed in 1578 by a gunshot wound to the head during a fight in the streets of [[Stirling]] with the followers of [[David Lindsay, 11th Earl of Crawford]]. Crawford was a good shot and Glamis presented an easy target as he was so tall, according to the historian [[David Hume of Godscroft]].<ref>David Reid, ed, ''History of the House of Angus'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 2005), pp. 242-3.</ref> His uncle [[Thomas Lyon (of Auldbar)|Thomas, Master of Glamis]] became head of the family, and tutor and curator of the young [[Lord Glamis]].\n\nIn 1601 he killed one of servants called Johnson, who had insulted him and shot at him in a churchyard in a Sunday. The king forgave him, and a church minister Mr Henry Blyth preached against this as contradictory to the king's vow to do justice.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), pp. 884, 891.</ref>\n\nPatrick was made [[Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne|Earl of Kinghorne]] in 1606.\n\nHe made a major restoration and reworking of [[Glamis Castle]] around the year 1606, commemorated by an inscription \"Built by Patrick, Lord Glamis, and D[ame] Anna Murray\" on the stair tower.\n\n==Family==\nIn May 1595 he married [[Anne Lyon, Countess of Kinghorne|Anne Murray]] who was reputed to be the mistress of [[James VI of Scotland]], at Stirling.<ref>''Scots Peerage'' (1911), p. 294: G. R. Hewitt, \u2018Lyon, John, eighth Lord Glamis (c.1544\u20131578)\u2019, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004.</ref> Neither James VI or [[Anne of Denmark]] attended the wedding because Anne was ill at [[Linlithgow Palace]]. The king and queen had planned to come to the wedding banquet on 1 June, to be celebrated with \"great triumph\" at [[Stirling Castle]].<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), nos. 533, 550, 556.</ref> Anne Murray was reported in May to be trying to make the wedding a peaceful occasion among feuds. The marriage was of political and factional significance in Scotland, controversially arranged by the [[John Erskine, Earl of Mar (1558\u20131634)|Earl of Mar]] without the knowledge of the Master of Glamis.<ref>''Calendar of State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 583.</ref> The Master of Glamis had wanted Patrick to marry a sister of the [[Robert Ker, 1st Earl of Roxburghe|Laird of Cessford]]. Mar's actions were part of his feud with the [[Chancellor of Scotland]], [[John Maitland, 1st Lord Maitland of Thirlestane|John Maitland of Thirlestane]].<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), nos. 527, 528, 530, 533, 534, 545.</ref>\n\nThe children of Anne and Patrick Lyon, 1st Earl of Kinghorne were:\n* James Lyon (d. August 1641)\n* Patrick Lyon\n* Frederick Lyon (d. 1660)\n* Anne Lyon (d. 8 February 1637), who married [[William Hay, 10th Earl of Erroll]].\n* Jean Lyon (d. 2 February 1618)\n* John Lyon, 2nd Earl of Kinghorne (13 August 1596 - 12 May 1646)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lyon, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1615 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish peers]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish peers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Patrick Lyon, 1st Earl of Kinghorne''' (c. 1575\u20131615) was a Scottish landowner.\n\nPatrick Lyon was the son of [[John Lyon, 8th Lord Glamis]] and Elizabeth Abernethy, only daughter of [[Alexander Abernethy, 6th Lord Saltoun]].\n[[File:Entrance to Glamis Castle - geograph.org.uk - 918221.jpg|thumb|right|The spiral stair at [[Glamis Castle]] was the work of Patrick Lyon, Earl of Kinghorne]]\nHis father was killed in 1578 by a gunshot wound to the head during a fight in the streets of [[Stirling]] with the followers of [[David Lindsay, 11th Earl of Crawford]]. Crawford was a good shot and Glamis presented an easy target as he was so tall, according to the historian [[David Hume of Godscroft]].<ref>David Reid, ed, ''History of the House of Angus'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 2005), pp. 242-3.</ref> His uncle [[Thomas Lyon (of Auldbar)|Thomas, Master of Glamis]] became head of the family, and tutor and curator of the young [[Lord Glamis]].\n\nIn 1601 he killed one of servants called Johnson, who had insulted him and shot at him in a churchyard in a Sunday. The king forgave him, and a church minister Mr Henry Blyth preached against this as cotradictory to the king's vow to do justice.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), pp. 884, 891.</ref>\n\nPatrick was made [[Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne|Earl of Kinghorne]] in 1606.\n\nHe made a major restoration and reworking of [[Glamis Castle]] around the year 1606, commemorated by an inscription \"Built by Patrick, Lord Glamis, and D[ame] Anna Murray\" on the stair tower.\n\n==Family==\nIn May 1595 he married [[Anne Lyon, Countess of Kinghorne|Anne Murray]] who was reputed to be the mistress of [[James VI of Scotland]], at Stirling.<ref>''Scots Peerage'' (1911), p. 294: G. R. Hewitt, \u2018Lyon, John, eighth Lord Glamis (c.1544\u20131578)\u2019, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004.</ref> Neither James VI or [[Anne of Denmark]] attended the wedding because Anne was ill at [[Linlithgow Palace]]. The king and queen had planned to come to the wedding banquet on 1 June, to be celebrated with \"great triumph\" at [[Stirling Castle]].<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), nos. 533, 550, 556.</ref> Anne Murray was reported in May to be trying to make the wedding a peaceful occasion among feuds. The marriage was of political and factional significance in Scotland, controversially arranged by the [[John Erskine, Earl of Mar (1558\u20131634)|Earl of Mar]] without the knowledge of the Master of Glamis.<ref>''Calendar of State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 583.</ref> The Master of Glamis had wanted Patrick to marry a sister of the [[Robert Ker, 1st Earl of Roxburghe|Laird of Cessford]]. Mar's actions were part of his feud with the [[Chancellor of Scotland]], [[John Maitland, 1st Lord Maitland of Thirlestane|John Maitland of Thirlestane]].<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), nos. 527, 528, 530, 533, 534, 545.</ref>\n\nThe children of Anne and Patrick Lyon, 1st Earl of Kinghorne were:\n* James Lyon (d. August 1641)\n* Patrick Lyon\n* Frederick Lyon (d. 1660)\n* Anne Lyon (d. 8 February 1637), who married [[William Hay, 10th Earl of Erroll]].\n* Jean Lyon (d. 2 February 1618)\n* John Lyon, 2nd Earl of Kinghorne (13 August 1596 - 12 May 1646)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lyon, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1615 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish peers]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish peers]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Lyon,_1st_Earl_of_Kinghorne"}
{"title_page": "Kaliko Kauahi", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n'''Kaliko Kauahi''' is an American actress known for her role as Sandra in the NBC comedy series [[Superstore (TV series)|Superstore]]. Additionally, she played the recurring role of Principal Kwan in the Disney Channel series [[Raven's Home|''Raven's Home'']] (2018-2019) and has had a variety of minor roles in TV and film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geekgirlauthority.com/gga-indigenerd-wire-interview-with-superstores-kaliko-kauahi/|title=GGA Indigenerd Wire: Interview with SUPERSTORE'S Kaliko Kauahi|last1=Harjo|first1=Noetta|date=8 July 2019|website=Geek Girl Authority}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/hall-pass/cast/308080/|title=Hall Pass TV Guide|website=TVGuide.com|language=en|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nKauahi was born and raised in [[Kauai|Kaua'i, Hawai'i]].<ref name=\"NBC Talent Bio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcumv.com/talent/kaliko-kauahi/bios_read_more?division=2&people=1|title=Kaliko Kauahi Talent Bio|website=NBC Universal Media Village|publisher=NBC|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> She attended [[Loyola Marymount University]] for college.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvinsider.com/817462/superstore-season-5-sandra-jerry-engaged-kaliko-kauahi/|title=Will 'Superstore's Sandra & Jerry Tie the Knot in Season 5? Kaliko Kauahi Fills Us In|last1=Snyder|first1=Diane|date=26 September 2019|website=TVInsider|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nShe began pursuing her acting career in her late 20s. She began with roles in short films, and eventually landed small parts on TV shows such as [[Parks and Recreation]] (2013), [[The Big Bang Theory]] (2014), and [[Brooklyn Nine-Nine]] (2015).<ref name=\"NBC Talent Bio\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geekgirlauthority.com/gga-indigenerd-wire-interview-with-superstores-kaliko-kauahi/|title=GGA Indigenerd Wire: Interview with SUPERSTORE'S Kalik